00:16:03,400 --> 00:16:11,400
we can start to fix that without having to change 
the whole whatever web framework, right? So I do  

188
00:16:11,400 --> 00:16:17,880
think there are ways to do these evolutions, but 
people really underestimate. They underestimate  

189
00:16:17,880 --> 00:16:24,600
the time to migrate stuff from the old system 
to the new system, is a huge, huge problem. 

190
00:16:24,600 --> 00:16:29,800
Particularly when you're talking about systems 
where you have sort of external people using the  

191
00:16:29,800 --> 00:16:36,680
system in some way, whether it's web UIs or APIs. 
You think, "Oh, we kind of know what's going on,  

192
00:16:36,680 --> 00:16:42,080
so it's not going to be that big a deal." 
Engineers notoriously, notoriously, notoriously,  

193
00:16:42,080 --> 00:16:48,920
massively underestimate the migration time 
for old system to new system and that causes  

194
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:52,680
a lot of problems. By the way, you still have to 
support the old system while you're working on  

195
00:16:52,680 --> 00:16:58,960
the new system. So I doubt many of the PMs in the 
audience are ever happy when they hear, we need  

196
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:06,200
to go away for six months, a year, two years to 
build this new thing and we just can't really  

197
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:11,840
add any features to the system in the interim.
That's infuriating, I'm sure, and frankly that's  

198
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:17,880
a problem and I don't know that that should be 
an acceptable answer in many cases. There may  

199
00:17:17,880 --> 00:17:24,320
occasionally again be a case where that is what 
has to happen, but I think most of the time you  

200
00:17:24,320 --> 00:17:27,760
can't really afford to just say we're going to go 
away and we're not going to touch the system for a  

201
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:32,120
long time and we're going to build something new 
over here. So many things about why that doesn't  

202
00:17:32,120 --> 00:17:39,240
make any sense. So this is a little bit of field 
of the blog post that you're referring to. So,  

203
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:44,760
if you've got a system that doesn't really need 
feature enhancement or development because it's  

204
00:17:44,760 --> 00:17:51,160
just sort of fine and the users are using it.
And it's just annoying to the engineers,  

205
00:17:51,160 --> 00:17:55,160
why in the world would you invest so much 
money in writing a new version of it? There's  

206
00:17:55,160 --> 00:18:00,320
a little bit of a cognitive dissonance that 
sometimes happens if you need to do new stuff  

207
00:18:00,320 --> 00:18:05,360
and the old system literally is not ... it's not 
possible to do the new stuff that you need to do,  

208
00:18:05,360 --> 00:18:08,960
you need to figure out a path to get to 
a sustainable system or you can continue  

209
00:18:08,960 --> 00:18:15,720
to add and evolve. You should be investing 
and so there does need to be an investment,  

210
00:18:15,720 --> 00:18:22,120
but you have to ask yourself, if I could go away 
and not touch this and not do anything to it for a  

211
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:28,240
long period of time without it really harming my 
business, is it worthwhile to change it at all? 

212
00:18:28,240 --> 00:18:35,320
Does it matter, and there's some questions there. 
I also think that when people try to do rewrites,  

213
00:18:35,320 --> 00:18:40,680
particularly again if it's something that 
you're really trying to just move to a new  

214
00:18:40,680 --> 00:18:45,200
language for example or sort of modernize in 
a certain way, [inaudible 00:18:45] a lot of  

215
00:18:45,200 --> 00:18:48,960
times people really underestimate what the old 
system does and how well they know what the old  

216
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:55,920
system does. There's so much logic buried in 
legacy systems, it tends to be undocumented,  

217
00:18:55,920 --> 00:18:58,880
it tends to be weird. You haven't 
thought through all the business rules,  

218
00:18:58,880 --> 00:19:08,800
you haven't thought through the data formatting 
and I think again, it's much, much harder to  

219
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:14,520
replicate all the important things from the old 
system to the new system than people expect. 

220
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:21,240
So there's more than that, but I do think 
sometimes you need to evolve systems and my  

221
00:19:21,240 --> 00:19:27,360
advice would be when you're struggling making an 
evolution plan, take pieces potentially of the old  

222
00:19:27,360 --> 00:19:33,920
system, uplift them, make them more scalable, make 
them easier to work with, clean up the tech debt,  

223
00:19:33,920 --> 00:19:37,840
but trying to say we're going to just go away. 
We're going to rewrite, we're going to build  

224
00:19:37,840 --> 00:19:42,640
something brand new and it's going to solve 
all our problems, it just very rarely works.

225
00:19:42,640 --> 00:19:46,760
I think a lot of PMs will be like, "Yes, thank 
you so much for saying this, because I think  

226
00:19:46,760 --> 00:19:51,960
that's also always a big struggle between the 
ENG team and the PM team." So just to summarize  

227
00:19:51,960 --> 00:19:55,240
what I think a lot of people miss or what you're 
saying a lot of people miss when they're thinking  

228
00:19:55,240 --> 00:20:00,000
about let's rewrite this thing, is the migration 
to the new system, migrating customers, users,  

229
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:04,240
data to the new thing is going to take a lot 
longer than you expect. You underestimate  

230
00:20:04,240 --> 00:20:10,040
knowing what it actually does and you're going 
to miss features and you can introduce new bugs.  

231
00:20:10,040 --> 00:20:15,160
This actually is very similar to what I've 
seen with redesigning a whole product flow. 

232
00:20:15,160 --> 00:20:19,000
There's always this sense of let's just 
rethink this onboarding flow from scratch  

233
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:25,320
or let's rebuild this part of the product and 
always it ends up being a negative experiment  

234
00:20:25,320 --> 00:20:29,320
result. It always ends up being less good and 
then, you have to spend all this time clawing  

235
00:20:29,320 --> 00:20:33,000
back to get to where you were and also, you 
forget the stuff that would ... the features  

236
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,480
that you had and you're like, "Oh, shit, I 
forgot about that feature, I forgot about that  

237
00:20:35,480 --> 00:20:41,440
feature." So it's interesting, there's a very 
similar situation in the product side. Okay,  

238
00:20:41,440 --> 00:20:45,680
amazing. I'm going to go to a slightly different 
topic, which is around engineering leadership. 

239
00:20:45,680 --> 00:20:48,840
So I know you've written a lot about 
engineering leadership, you spent a lot  

240
00:20:48,840 --> 00:20:53,000
of times with engineering leaders, so I have a 
few questions here. One is that I know that one  

241
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:58,760
of the things that haunts engineering leaders 
most is finding the balance between staying  

242
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:03,440
technical and their technical expertise, and 
their leadership expertise and basically finding  

243
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:08,640
the right altitude of how high ... where to be 
in the org and also how in the details to be,  

244
00:21:08,640 --> 00:21:13,320
and also staying technical enough to be relevant. 
What have you learned in your own experience  

245
00:21:13,320 --> 00:21:18,080
of finding that balance and how do you advise 
engineering leaders as they struggle with this?

246
00:21:18,080 --> 00:21:27,080
Yeah, so one piece of advice I give everybody is 
don't stop being a hands-on technical until you  

247
00:21:27,080 --> 00:21:34,320
feel like it's in your bones. You feel like 
you've got mastery that you could ... if you  

248
00:21:34,320 --> 00:21:38,640
know a second language fluently or 
if you played an instrument really,  

249
00:21:38,640 --> 00:21:43,160
really seriously for a long time or maybe a 
sport really, really seriously for a long time,  

250
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:48,040
you'll be familiar with the ... I haven't done 
that in a long time, but if I was to pick it up,  

251
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:52,360
it would be rusty, but I would get there pretty 
quickly, right? Maybe physically, I wouldn't be  

252
00:21:52,360 --> 00:21:58,200
as strong as I was or whatever, but I would 
get there. You can do that with writing code. 

253
00:21:58,200 --> 00:22:02,960
You can do that with technical skills if you 
do it for long enough, I think you can develop  

254
00:22:02,960 --> 00:22:08,920
sort of a baseline mastery, where you're 
not going to be as fast and a lot of the  

255
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:12,520
challenges of being technical is actually in 
all the tooling and all the tooling evolution,  

256
00:22:12,520 --> 00:22:15,800
but you're not going to be necessarily 
as fast as people who have been doing it,  

257
00:22:15,800 --> 00:22:20,240
but you won't be completely clueless and I 
think that all the things you learn getting  

258
00:22:20,240 --> 00:22:29,120
to that really comfortable mastery of some part 
of hands-on tech will stay with you and will help  

259
00:22:29,120 --> 00:22:35,800
you just maintain a level of confidence in your 
own technical know-how and maintain a level of  

260
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:41,120
empathy for what it means to be a good engineer.
And I think just make you a lot less anxious about  

261
00:22:41,120 --> 00:22:46,120
being hands-off, even though I think everybody 
who makes that transition for a year or two,  

262
00:22:46,120 --> 00:22:50,520
especially if you're really have to be hands-off 
or you just don't have time to write code at all,  

263
00:22:50,520 --> 00:22:54,920
you are going to be anxious for a while 
no matter what. The things to then think  

264
00:22:54,920 --> 00:23:02,160
about from that point is, being technical is 
also just about knowing what's going on and  

265
00:23:02,160 --> 00:23:09,760
paying attention and being able to ask ... what 
people care about with technical leaders in my  

266
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:14,320
experience is they want people who actually seem 
like they sort of understand what you're doing  

267
00:23:14,320 --> 00:23:20,840
and can ask good questions and help guide you 
to better decisions without actually being the  

268
00:23:20,840 --> 00:23:24,920
one who's like, "Oh no, you need to use 
this library instead of that library." 

269
00:23:25,520 --> 00:23:30,080
It's actually sort of annoying when somebody 
that's very senior and hands-off tries to tell  

270
00:23:30,080 --> 00:23:33,960
you, don't use this library, use that 
library because I don't know about you,  

271
00:23:33,960 --> 00:23:38,760
but I don't really believe people who have been 
hands-off for that long when they try to tell me  

272
00:23:38,760 --> 00:23:43,360
what to do and the thing that I'm kind of the 
expert in right now, but I do appreciate it  

273
00:23:43,360 --> 00:23:49,200
when I'm given more guidance around, well, have 
you considered this? Tell me about how you're  

274
00:23:49,200 --> 00:23:55,120
planning to handle that situation. What are the 
major technical challenges with implementing this  

275
00:23:55,120 --> 00:24:00,880
and that can actually spend the time to listen 
and ask thoughtful questions on the back of that. 

276
00:24:00,880 --> 00:24:06,720
The last thing I would say is surround 
yourself with smart technical people,  

277
00:24:06,720 --> 00:24:14,040
also as much as you can, and be willing to 
listen to them, talk about tech and ask them  

278
00:24:14,040 --> 00:24:20,640
questions about things. I feel like that's part 
of the reason that I am able to stay technically  

279
00:24:20,640 --> 00:24:26,280
savvy and credible amongst people who work for 
me is not that I'm writing code because I'm not.  

280
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:32,520
But I am listening to a lot of very smart people 
talk about technology a lot, down to the level  

281
00:24:32,520 --> 00:24:38,320
of I'm trying to debug this database issue, what 
the heck is going on? And just constantly being  

282
00:24:38,320 --> 00:24:44,080
interested in those stories and learning from 
them and learning what really smart engineers  

283
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:49,440
are thinking about and worrying about.
The more you can build that network of  

284
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:55,760
people that are still hands-on and stay in 
touch with that, I do think that helps a lot.

285
00:24:55,760 --> 00:24:58,000
So on my last point, how are 
you actually doing that? Is it  

286
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:01,360
watching ... going to conferences 
with friends, something else?

287
00:25:01,360 --> 00:25:08,720
Yeah, yeah. I mean, I guess for me it started 
with going to conferences, meeting people. Now,  

288
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:15,200
I'm in a lot of different chat groups where 
people are just sort of regularly communicating,  

289
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:21,640
staying in touch with ... staying in touch with 
former colleagues. I will admit I'm kind of a  

290
00:25:21,640 --> 00:25:27,280
social person and I have a big network, 
so this may be easier said than done,  

291
00:25:27,280 --> 00:25:34,960
but I do think being in the right group chats ... 
I also think, I'm sure reading various tech news  

292
00:25:34,960 --> 00:25:40,360
and tech sort of commentary and discussion 
boards, I mean it's definitely a mixed bag  

293
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:45,080
of that stuff I think that like ... but there are 
smart people. You find the smart people in there,  

294
00:25:45,080 --> 00:25:50,920
you sort of follow what they're saying. I think 
that's another good way to keep that perspective.

295
00:25:50,920 --> 00:25:53,640
Is it a sign, I wonder if you're 
not interested in that anymore that  

296
00:25:53,640 --> 00:25:57,240
maybe you should move into something 
else. I don't know. If you're like,  

297
00:25:57,240 --> 00:26:00,800
don't really pay attention 
to engineering technicalness.

298
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:08,720
It's hard for me to say because I'm such a 
nerd. I really love tech. I'm in this industry,  

299
00:26:08,720 --> 00:26:14,560
because I'm just actually genuinely 
very interested in certain corners,  

300
00:26:14,560 --> 00:26:18,920
not every corner of technology but certain 
corners of technology. I want to know what  

301
00:26:18,920 --> 00:26:25,560
the latest stuff that's happening in databases and 
infrastructure and I find it all very interesting.  

302
00:26:25,560 --> 00:26:31,080
I find the problems interesting. So I think that 
makes me very successful because I just have that  

303
00:26:31,080 --> 00:26:36,600
natural curiosity and passion and interest in it. 
But I don't know that that's a total prerequisite.

304
00:26:36,600 --> 00:26:41,440
Yeah, but you've been talking about ... it reminds 
me a little bit of this guy, LevelsIO on Twitter.  

305
00:26:41,440 --> 00:26:44,760
Have you heard of this guy? He was just on 
Lex Friedman. Have you listened to that yet?

306
00:26:44,760 --> 00:26:48,040
I think maybe I saw a clip of 
it, but I haven't listened to it.

307
00:26:48,040 --> 00:26:51,800
So I think one of the most successful indie 
engineers where he just works on his own thing  

308
00:26:51,800 --> 00:26:55,760
all by himself, never raises money, just 
launch his products that make money. And  

309
00:26:55,760 --> 00:27:01,600
a funny thing about him is he works ... all 
stuff is in PHP and jQuery. He's just like,  

310
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:07,240
this works. I've always had this to do, learn 
Node.js, learn Python. And I'm like, I'm too busy  

311
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:11,440
to build ... while I'm building to learn these 
new things and he's been incredibly successful.  

312
00:27:11,440 --> 00:27:16,040
So it touches on sometimes maybe you don't need 
to just keep rewriting to the newest frameworks.

313
00:27:16,040 --> 00:27:20,880
Yeah, no, I mean look, I actually ... I feel like 
I know a lot of smart engineers who are in that  

314
00:27:20,880 --> 00:27:29,240
category. They're like, we built amazing things 
in PHP and relatively simple SQL and so much  

315
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:36,840
of tech is over-engineering things and I don't 
totally disagree. I think the challenge is though,  

316
00:27:36,840 --> 00:27:43,040
of course, what works as a one person show, 
doesn't always work in a scaled organization  

317
00:27:43,040 --> 00:27:51,120
for better or for worse, we're in different like, 
you've got to match what makes one person really  

318
00:27:51,120 --> 00:28:01,000
productive. Will it make 100 people, 1000 people, 
even 10 people really productive? That's always a  

319
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:07,320
little hard to tell and that's why I do think you 
should be not ... I think it's always a good idea  

320
00:28:07,320 --> 00:28:12,400
to be keeping up with what's happening and what's 
changing in whatever kind of side of tech you're  

321
00:28:12,400 --> 00:28:18,280
in, but not obsessively chasing every fad.
I think being aware of, but not necessarily  

322
00:28:18,280 --> 00:28:23,800
chasing them, but particularly, if you're working 
in groups, teams, larger companies, even midsize  

323
00:28:23,800 --> 00:28:30,480
companies, there is some amount of, you're 
balancing the tech that makes one person go fast  

324
00:28:30,480 --> 00:28:35,760
with the tech that makes 10 or 100 people go fast 
and those are not always exactly the same thing.

325
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:39,840
Just to kind follow this thread a little bit 
and to kind of nerd snipe you a little bit,  

326
00:28:39,840 --> 00:28:44,320
is there a platform or language or framework 
these days that you're either very excited  

327
00:28:44,320 --> 00:28:46,600
about that you think is helping 
people move faster and do better  

328
00:28:46,600 --> 00:28:52,080
work or the opposite just like this is ... 
everyone is excited but this is not good.

329
00:28:52,080 --> 00:28:58,040
I will say this, one example I actually 
put in my own notes for this conversation  

330
00:28:58,920 --> 00:29:04,680
was GraphQL. I would not tell a team to use 
or not use GraphQL at this point because it's  

331
00:29:04,680 --> 00:29:10,240
a bit out of my expertise zone and my level 
of management. It's not really my job anyway,  

332
00:29:10,240 --> 00:29:19,880
but it is one of the things that is both popular 
and thought relatively poorly of by most of the  

333
00:29:19,880 --> 00:29:27,160
senior people that I know. And so, I guess 
I would say that's one where I would say if  

334
00:29:27,160 --> 00:29:35,200
you're seriously thinking about it and you're 
not Facebook, you may really want to make sure  

335
00:29:35,200 --> 00:29:39,720
you know what problem you're trying to solve 
because the impression that I have from sort  

336
00:29:39,720 --> 00:29:45,200
of listening to people talk about it is 
that GraphQL is kind of trying to promise  

337
00:29:45,200 --> 00:29:48,920
front-end engineers that they don't really 
have to collaborate with backend engineers. 

338
00:29:48,920 --> 00:29:52,280
And they can just sort of build whatever 
and it'll all be fine, and it just doesn't  

339
00:29:52,280 --> 00:29:56,600
ever seem to work out that well for anybody who 
actually does it in practice. Again, obviously,  

340
00:29:56,600 --> 00:30:00,880
it can work out that well because Facebook 
has made a great go of it. I'm sure there are  

341
00:30:00,880 --> 00:30:06,960
other companies that are, but that's one where 
it's not that new but it remains one of these  

342
00:30:06,960 --> 00:30:13,760
things where it seems like an interesting 
fad that maybe is burning a lot of people.

343
00:30:13,760 --> 00:30:18,120
That's awesome. I appreciate you sharing that. I 
don't know if this is exactly an example of this,  

344
00:30:18,120 --> 00:30:21,560
but on that podcast levels, I forget 
his actual name, Peter I think,  

345
00:30:21,560 --> 00:30:26,680
shared that whenever there's a framework 
