00:49:23,440 --> 00:49:27,480
I think there's different approaches you 
could take, right? One approach you could  

554
00:49:27,480 --> 00:49:33,240
take is just like every Friday I'm going to 
stop working at 4 PM or something, let's say,  

555
00:49:33,240 --> 00:49:40,640
and I am not, or I'm not going to let myself 
work this weekend. Forcing yourself to log off,  

556
00:49:40,640 --> 00:49:52,480
forcing yourself to have boundaries and saying 
... and then doing out of what did I get done,  

557
00:49:52,480 --> 00:50:00,720
I think can help. That's scary. And people don't 
like doing that, but I do think that that's one  

558
00:50:00,720 --> 00:50:05,040
of the best ways to do it is really just saying, 
I'm going to log off. I'm going to log off every  

559
00:50:05,040 --> 00:50:10,640
day this week at 6 PM. I'm going to ... because 
your brain is probably going to keep thinking. 

560
00:50:10,640 --> 00:50:13,920
You might still be a little stressed out, you're 
still thinking about work, you're still worrying  

561
00:50:13,920 --> 00:50:18,880
about it, but there is a difference between 
thinking about it and doing it, and particularly  

562
00:50:18,880 --> 00:50:23,760
for those of you who are earlier in your careers, 
this was actually, I think one of the reasons that  

563
00:50:23,760 --> 00:50:31,200
I did get to mastery was because I was extremely 
good at being focused when I was at work, when I  

564
00:50:31,200 --> 00:50:38,320
was a hands-on programmer and really writing code 
for many of the hours of the day. And that meant  

565
00:50:38,320 --> 00:50:45,160
I was not ... this was pre heavy social media. 
I was much less distracted, which I don't know  

566
00:50:45,160 --> 00:50:50,200
if I would be able to do it in the modern era 
as easily, but having that real heavy focus  

567
00:50:50,200 --> 00:50:54,720
time because I was like, "I don't want to work on 
the weekend. I don't want to stay here until 9 PM  

568
00:50:54,720 --> 00:50:58,840
every night. I just want to get this done." And 
it meant that I didn't do quite as many copies. 

569
00:50:58,840 --> 00:51:05,880
I didn't go to lunch and chat with people all 
every day, but I was very, very productive and  

570
00:51:05,880 --> 00:51:11,040
I learned to get a lot done in a short period of 
time. And I do think learning those skills earlier  

571
00:51:11,040 --> 00:51:16,640
in your career and then continuing to apply them 
throughout your career is another piece of advice.

572
00:51:16,640 --> 00:51:19,120
In terms of staying and getting 
focused, is there anything that  

573
00:51:19,120 --> 00:51:24,600
helps you focus? Is it like headphones, 
a drink? What gets you in the zone?

574
00:51:24,600 --> 00:51:31,400
I mean, yeah, I have a lot of rituals. 
I have my caffeination rituals.

575
00:51:31,400 --> 00:51:32,400
Say more.

576
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:36,440
Well, I mean I can't drink coffee anymore because 
my stomach got messed up at some point, but I  

577
00:51:36,440 --> 00:51:44,240
drink tea in the morning. I drink caffeinated 
water also. I have a Diet Coke at lunch,  

578
00:51:44,240 --> 00:51:55,920
so I have these rituals of my caffeine hits that 
help me. I have to be in a quiet place. I do find  

579
00:51:56,600 --> 00:52:04,880
non-music that is ... I really like Four Tet, for 
example, as music to focus or the new Andre 3000  

580
00:52:04,880 --> 00:52:10,760
Flute album is extremely good for focusing, 
where it's not quite predictable, no lyrics  

581
00:52:10,760 --> 00:52:16,840
and not quite predictable. For me, that helps me 
focus a lot. I can't be listening to any words  

582
00:52:16,840 --> 00:52:24,360
and focus. My brain just cannot ignore words. So 
those are some of the things I use to help folks.

583
00:52:24,360 --> 00:52:28,800
That is awesome. I have a similar caffeine 
strategy. I'm drinking tea always during these  

584
00:52:28,800 --> 00:52:32,600
podcasts and this little thing I got here and 
then, my wife doesn't want me to drink Diet Coke  

585
00:52:32,600 --> 00:52:36,320
because she thinks the sugar and it is not good, 
but I still drink it sometimes and it works great.  

586
00:52:36,320 --> 00:52:40,400
I switched to green tea. That's my approach. 
Start with black tea and then switch to green tea.

587
00:52:40,400 --> 00:52:41,440
That's smart.

588
00:52:41,440 --> 00:52:44,520
Man, there's so many things you shared 
that I wanted to dig into. Let me share  

589
00:52:44,520 --> 00:52:49,360
a couple of things. Your point about delegating I 
thought was really important, and there's another  

590
00:52:49,360 --> 00:52:56,000
benefit to learning to delegate, which is team 
members feel empowered. You give them a chance to  

591
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:02,520
take on responsibility and they feel like I have 
an opportunity to show I can do this other thing.

592
00:53:02,520 --> 00:53:07,000
Yeah, and you're never going 
to scale if you don't delegate.

593
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:11,120
Yeah, and it's hard to start learning to 
do that, but once you get good at it, it  

594
00:53:11,120 --> 00:53:16,560
becomes so great. I love just delegate everything 
every time, and people enjoy it. They're like,  

595
00:53:16,560 --> 00:53:22,480
"Amazing. You're giving me opportunity." The thing 
you said about how ... if you're not sometimes  

596
00:53:22,480 --> 00:53:26,680
regretting something you cut or potentially 
firing someone you don't regret, Elon actually,  

597
00:53:26,680 --> 00:53:30,600
Elon Musk has a great approach to this. I don't 
know if you've heard his philosophy on optimizing.  

598
00:53:30,600 --> 00:53:34,680
He has this whole five-step process of 
figuring out how to optimize something,  

599
00:53:34,680 --> 00:53:41,120
and one of them is try to cut things like, do we 
need this thing or not? And if you don't recognize  

600
00:53:41,120 --> 00:53:45,160
that 10% of stuff you cut, it was a mistake, 
you're probably not cutting enough stuff.

601
00:53:45,160 --> 00:53:52,840
You'll have to figure out your own metrics. 
But I definitely think testing the limits,  

602
00:53:52,840 --> 00:53:57,560
it's scary though. I'm going to be 
honest. Doing that is always scary.  

603
00:53:57,560 --> 00:54:03,120
It brings up like, I forgot to finish 
the assignment nightmares of school,  

604
00:54:04,240 --> 00:54:11,080
especially for the overachievers that often end 
up in these kinds of companies and jobs. Again,  

605
00:54:11,080 --> 00:54:14,200
you got to do things that scare 
you or you're never going to grow.

606
00:54:14,960 --> 00:54:18,000
Okay, I'm going to go in a whole different 
direction. You've got a book coming out  

607
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:21,920
about platform engineering and platform 
teams. This is something that I get a lot  

608
00:54:21,920 --> 00:54:25,480
of questions about. A lot of people are 
thinking about moving to a platform team  

609
00:54:25,480 --> 00:54:30,280
or struggling working on a platform team or 
struggling working with a platform team. So I  

610
00:54:30,280 --> 00:54:34,960
have a bunch of questions along these lines. 
The first is I asked a bunch of people that  

611
00:54:34,960 --> 00:54:39,640
worked with you what to ask you and someone 
that worked with you shared this quote about  

612
00:54:39,640 --> 00:54:44,160
his frustration working with platform teams 
that he's often complaining to you about and  

613
00:54:44,160 --> 00:54:48,120
he works on customer-facing products. And so, 
he said platform teams that are often slow. 

614
00:54:48,120 --> 00:54:51,840
They're often pushing us to compromise on 
features to adopt their systems. They often  

615
00:54:51,840 --> 00:54:58,240
get infinite funding even though they don't 
have to show any ROI. And so, maybe from the  

616
00:54:58,240 --> 00:55:02,760
perspective of working with a platform team, 
say you're building something customer-facing,  

617
00:55:02,760 --> 00:55:08,080
any tips for effectively working with a platform 
team and building a great relationship there.

618
00:55:08,080 --> 00:55:13,560
I'm very sympathetic to anybody who feels that way 
because part of the reason that I wrote this book,  

619
00:55:13,560 --> 00:55:20,880
I co-wrote it with a friend, Ian Nolan, is that so 
many platform teams are guilty of all the things  

620
00:55:20,880 --> 00:55:26,960
that he's complaining about, that my friend 
was complaining about, that they don't listen,  

621
00:55:26,960 --> 00:55:34,280
they're not delivering effectively, they're not 
explaining their value to the company. And it is  

622
00:55:34,280 --> 00:55:41,400
infuriating when you're dealing with that. And 
honestly, I'm very sympathetic. The thing that  

623
00:55:41,400 --> 00:55:50,840
I would say though is the more you can, first 
of all, spend the time understanding that the  

624
00:55:50,840 --> 00:55:57,880
platform team's problems a little bit and trying 
to collaborate and work with them and be clear  

625
00:55:57,880 --> 00:56:01,720
about what it is you actually need and how you're 
willing to work with them, I think the better. 

626
00:56:01,720 --> 00:56:11,840
I think if you get mad and you just try to avoid 
them or undermine them or whatever, that may  

627
00:56:11,840 --> 00:56:17,160
work in the long run, but it's just going to make 
everything worse in the short run. So I do think  

628
00:56:17,160 --> 00:56:24,080
that if you've got a platform team that you're 
frustrated with, some tips, I would put are like,  

629
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:28,600
"Look, find the parts of that team that are good 
because I'm sure there are some," right? Maybe the  

630
00:56:28,600 --> 00:56:35,640
databases team is awesome. And really make sure 
you are maintaining a good relationship with that  

631
00:56:35,640 --> 00:56:40,280
part of the team and you can point to how you 
are collaborating extremely well with that part  

632
00:56:40,280 --> 00:56:46,120
of the team. Help give them product feedback.
This is annoying but sometimes needs to happen  

633
00:56:46,120 --> 00:56:49,960
because a lot of companies, I actually 
think product ... you need to have a  

634
00:56:49,960 --> 00:56:53,440
product mindset and frankly, you need to have 
product managers to build good platforms,  

635
00:56:53,440 --> 00:56:56,680
internal platforms. A lot of companies just 
don't do this. They don't believe that they  

636
00:56:56,680 --> 00:57:02,040
should waste head count on product managers for 
internal teams. So you end up with this platform  

637
00:57:02,040 --> 00:57:06,000
team that has a lot of smart engineers, but they 
don't really know what to build. So they're just  

638
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:10,960
sort of building whatever they think is right. And 
so sometimes your job is to product manage them,  

639
00:57:10,960 --> 00:57:16,280
is to tell them, these are the problems 
that we have and this is what we need. 

640
00:57:16,280 --> 00:57:21,880
And the clearer you can be about that, 
particularly when they don't have a product team,  

641
00:57:21,880 --> 00:57:26,280
oftentimes, you can kind of lead them from 
the side in that way. And so I think that's  

642
00:57:26,280 --> 00:57:30,920
another approach that I would take when 
you're in that situation. Find the parts  

643
00:57:30,920 --> 00:57:36,280
of the team that are working and working well 
with your team and make sure you develop those  

644
00:57:36,280 --> 00:57:42,320
relationships and try to just get over the anger 
and frustration and just be clear about what  

645
00:57:42,320 --> 00:57:48,160
it is that you need and help them understand 
what they should really be doing and building.

646
00:57:48,160 --> 00:57:52,520
That is really interesting advice. So especially, 
you're saying if they don't have a PM helping,  

647
00:57:52,520 --> 00:57:58,760
make sure they're guiding things well, is you 
can help them ... basically help them think  

648
00:57:58,760 --> 00:58:03,200
through stuff that will benefit them and also, 
help the stuff that you're trying to get done.

649
00:58:03,200 --> 00:58:03,840
Yeah.

650
00:58:03,840 --> 00:58:07,880
That's awesome advice. Okay, so what 
about from the leadership perspective,  

651
00:58:07,880 --> 00:58:11,520
trying to build an effective platform 
team, do you have any advice on how  

652
00:58:11,520 --> 00:58:17,200
to structure these teams and incentivize 
these teams to help them be successful?

653
00:58:17,200 --> 00:58:22,720
First of all, I'm a very strong believer that 
platform engineering has to involve software  

654
00:58:22,720 --> 00:58:27,600
engineering. If you don't have any software 
engineers on your platform team and you only  

655
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:34,400
have more operations systems engineers, DevOps, 
SRE, which I realize there are some SREs that are  

656
00:58:34,400 --> 00:58:38,760
software engineers, but they tend to not want 
to write big software. I think you're kind of  

657
00:58:38,760 --> 00:58:46,120
missing the picture. Platform engineering is 
not just maintaining cloud infrastructure and  

658
00:58:46,120 --> 00:58:53,920
doing small scripts or blueprints or enablement 
projects for other teams, because that doesn't  

659
00:58:53,920 --> 00:59:01,560
really create a cohesive and coherent platform. 
It doesn't create products and frankly you need  

660
00:59:01,560 --> 00:59:07,280
to be ... platforms are products, ultimately.
You should be thinking about how do I create  

661
00:59:07,280 --> 00:59:13,560
coherent offerings that make this company more 
productive? So you need software engineers. Yes,  

662
00:59:13,560 --> 00:59:18,480
you need sort of operations systems, 
SRE specialists as well. And of course,  

663
00:59:18,480 --> 00:59:26,440
you need product people. I had product teams on 
... product managers for all of my platform teams.  

664
00:59:26,440 --> 00:59:32,000
I've really developed out that practice in 
the companies that I've worked for doing this  

665
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:39,920
because I just believe that you're not going to 
get great results if you just believe that to  

666
00:59:39,920 --> 00:59:43,840
engineers and engineering management. They 
will do their best and you do occasionally  

667
00:59:43,840 --> 00:59:49,000
find engineers that have really great product 
instincts in this space, but the actual details. 

668
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:55,680
And focus of the product work is just you can't 
write a bunch of code and/or manage a big software  

669
00:59:55,680 --> 00:59:59,320
engineering team and be a product manager at the 
same time. That's actually just asking, I think,  

670
00:59:59,320 --> 01:00:04,200
too much of people to do that really well, at 
least for very long. So I think when it comes to  

671
01:00:04,200 --> 01:00:11,720
structuring a team, recognize this is not just 
like SRE V2. This is more than that. You want  

672
01:00:11,720 --> 01:00:17,720
software engineers, you want systems engineers, 
you want product people. And then, one of the  

673
01:00:17,720 --> 01:00:23,480
reasons you want product folks is because 
you want to be thinking about impact-based,  

674
01:00:23,480 --> 01:00:31,960
outcome-based approaches, not just like, "Well, 
we built this thing that seemed cool, we adopted  

675
01:00:31,960 --> 01:00:36,520
this technology from this company because that's 
what everybody on the internet is talking about." 

676
01:00:36,520 --> 01:00:44,920
Whether it's VC funded or big company. We actually 
thought about what are the problems the engineers  

677
01:00:44,920 --> 01:00:51,440
at my company are facing? How can we improve their 
productivity or deliver leverage to this business  

678
01:00:51,440 --> 01:00:55,920
through whatever it is we're building, right? Are 
we reducing the cycle time for engineering tasks?  

679
01:00:56,480 --> 01:01:04,640
Are we solving problems that are preventing 
products from launching and scaling? Are we making  

680
01:01:04,640 --> 01:01:11,720
really meaningful cost reductions or efficiencies 
and, in our products or in our platforms? These  

681
01:01:11,720 --> 01:01:19,480
are some examples of measurable contributions, 
but I think one of the challenges is that people  

682
01:01:19,480 --> 01:01:26,120
create these platform teams and think that they 
can be sort of divorced from having an impact  

683
01:01:26,120 --> 01:01:29,160
focus because it's like, "Well, you just got to 
run the infrastructure and make sure it works." 

684
01:01:29,160 --> 01:01:33,240
And it's like, "No, you actually do still 
have to do ... if you do that OKR stuff or  

685
01:01:33,240 --> 01:01:39,560
goal setting," or whatever, you've got to take 
a lot of the best practices of product. It's a  

686
01:01:39,560 --> 01:01:45,640
little different in the internal world, but it's 
still very important if you want to do platforms.

687
01:01:45,640 --> 01:01:48,280
On the line of having PMs within 
the platform teams. Some of the  

688
01:01:48,280 --> 01:01:52,960
best PMs I've ever worked with where PMs 
on platform teams, and that just tells me,  

689
01:01:52,960 --> 01:01:57,240
it's not like where you put PMs that are just 
meant like that's ... where you could have some  

690
01:01:57,240 --> 01:02:01,400
of the highest leverage because platform teams 
enable the rest of the company to move faster.

691
01:02:01,400 --> 01:02:02,000
Yeah.

692
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:06,240
And one difference there, I'm curious if 
you agree, is your ratio of PM to engineer  

693
01:02:06,240 --> 01:02:10,480
can be a lot higher. You can have a lot 
more engineers per PM on platform teams.

694
01:02:10,480 --> 01:02:15,680
Yeah. Yeah, I think that's right because 
I think so much of the work in a platform  

695
01:02:15,680 --> 01:02:25,040
team is not exactly product work. A lot of it is 
like scaling or really deep kind of technical,  

696
01:02:25,040 --> 01:02:30,080
like I got to figure out how to actually do 
this technical thing or I've got to do this  

697
01:02:30,080 --> 01:02:35,960
performance efficiency and you don't always 
need a product spec for that, right? It is  

698
01:02:35,960 --> 01:02:42,840
often just a very engineering heavy task. So yes, 
I think the ratios do tend to be a bit different.

699
01:02:42,840 --> 01:02:47,280
We dove over right into this topic. Maybe it 
might be helpful to help people understand what  

700
01:02:47,280 --> 01:02:51,480
is a platform team, just what are examples of 
teams that would be considered platform teams.

701
01:02:51,480 --> 01:02:55,840
I mean, I guess the high level definition 
that I have of platform engineering is if  

702
01:02:55,840 --> 01:03:01,760
you are developing and operating platforms 
that ... where they're trying to manage  

703
01:03:01,760 --> 01:03:08,320
overall system complexity and deliver 
leverage to your business. So a lot  

704
01:03:08,320 --> 01:03:11,640
of the teams that people think about nowadays 
and when they're talking about platform teams,  

705
01:03:11,640 --> 01:03:16,840
they're talking a lot about teams that may have 
formerly been called dev tools. For example,  

706
01:03:16,840 --> 01:03:28,160
so your CI/CD tooling for the company, a lot of 
the cloud infrastructure provisioning and tooling.  

707
01:03:28,160 --> 01:03:35,240
If you're at a company with certain technical 
problems, you may very well be building semi  

708
01:03:35,240 --> 01:03:40,520
bespoke storage systems. For example, maybe part 
of your platform teams. I actually think that  

709
01:03:40,520 --> 01:03:50,440
there are ... And then, actually web frameworks 
... Web mobile framework and support for that. 

710
01:03:50,440 --> 01:03:55,720
That set of engineering can also be part of a 
platform offering. I actually kind of believe that  

711
01:03:56,480 --> 01:04:01,200
there's also sort of what you might call 
integration platforms or platforms that are in  

712
01:04:01,200 --> 01:04:07,880
between that infrastructurey developer tooly stuff 
and products. So billing platforms for example,  

713
01:04:07,880 --> 01:04:13,200
if you have a single billing platform for all 
of the different products in your company,  

714
01:04:13,200 --> 01:04:19,120
that shares a lot of overlaps in the 
challenges of those more dev tools,  

715
01:04:19,120 --> 01:04:23,760
infrastructurey platform teams because you're 
probably supporting lots of different product  

716
01:04:23,760 --> 01:04:31,480
lines that are using this system that needs to 
be able to scale with certain efficiencies. You  

717
01:04:31,480 --> 01:04:35,000
need to still do the product discovery.
You probably have a little bit more of  

718
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:44,640
a business product focus than the pure internal 
tools teams, but that gets to the blended area.

719
01:04:44,640 --> 01:04:49,400
For founders that are earlier stage or companies 
that are smaller hearing this and they're like,  

720
01:04:49,400 --> 01:04:53,680
"Oh, shit do I need a platform team?" 
So yeah, you're shaking your head,  

721
01:04:53,680 --> 01:04:57,960
if people aren't watching on YouTube. What's 
a sign that's time maybe to start creating  

722
01:04:57,960 --> 01:05:00,720
a platform team and setting aside 
resources for something like that?

723
01:05:00,720 --> 01:05:06,840
So first of all, I think it gets to be like, you 
have 50 plus engineers. I don't think this is  

724
01:05:06,840 --> 01:05:18,400
the kind of thing that you start when you are 10 
engineers, right? But when you are ... so there's  

725
01:05:18,400 --> 01:05:23,400
a lot of ad hoc coordination that's probably 
happening amongst your engineering groups right  

726
01:05:23,400 --> 01:05:30,800
now, where maybe you just have one ... you have 
your GitHub and somebody is making sure that all  

727
01:05:30,800 --> 01:05:40,120
of that stuff is sort of working. You have a few 
cloud databases and you got a couple of people  

728
01:05:40,120 --> 01:05:45,520
on each team and they kind of share notes to 
figure out what's going on or whatever. Okay,  

729
01:05:45,520 --> 01:05:51,360
it's all good, but at some point, you hit either 
a lot of inefficiency where you're seeing the  

730
01:05:51,360 --> 01:05:57,440
same people across a bunch of different teams.
Each team has the same kind of people having to  

731
01:05:57,440 --> 01:06:02,000
solve the same kinds of problems. It just seems 
like why do I have three people in every team,  

732
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:06,560
dealing with this instead of centralizing it 
and making it a little more efficient. It also  

733
01:06:06,560 --> 01:06:13,320
could be that you hit some core scaling issue that 
starts to really need a dedicated team to solve.  

734
01:06:13,320 --> 01:06:17,760
Again, that could be developer productivity. 
Every development team is trying to do it their  

735
01:06:17,760 --> 01:06:24,320
own way and everybody is just super slow because 
you just can't get code released and it all has  

736
01:06:24,320 --> 01:06:28,320
to be coordinated across every different team and 
it's just like, what is going on? We need to fix  

737
01:06:28,320 --> 01:06:36,200
that or you actually have a technical challenging 
area that needs a focused team to fix the scaling. 

